/* CISA :: content/pbqs.js — CISA performance-based question database (30). */
window.CISA = window.CISA || {}; CISA.pbqs = CISA.pbqs || [];
CISA.pbqs.push.apply(CISA.pbqs, [
{"id":"PBQ-01","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1A3","title":"Scoping the annual IS audit plan","brief":"You are building the risk-based annual audit plan and must direct effort toward the areas that matter most.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — RISK-BASED PLANNING UNIVERSE","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>ENGAGEMENT:</span> FY25 annual IS audit plan\n<span class='cy'>AUDITABLE UNITS (residual risk after controls):</span>\n  A. Payroll batch interface .......... HIGH  (last audited 3 yrs ago)\n  B. Cafeteria POS reconciliation ..... LOW   (last audited 1 yr ago)\n  C. Internet-facing patient portal ... HIGH  (never audited; new)\n  D. Print-server share permissions ... LOW   (stable, no change)\n<span class='dim'>Note: audit budget covers ~2 of 4 units this cycle.</span>","fields":[{"label":"Which principle should drive where audit resources are concentrated?","hint":"Risk-based audit planning","options":["Audit every unit equally so coverage is uniform across the universe","Concentrate effort on the units with the highest residual risk","Prioritize the units that are cheapest and fastest to audit"],"answer":1,"explain":"Risk-based planning directs finite audit resources toward the areas of greatest residual risk. 'Concentrate effort on the units with the highest residual risk' is correct because it maximizes assurance where a control failure would hurt most. 'Audit every unit equally' ignores risk and wastes budget on low-risk units. 'Prioritize the units that are cheapest and fastest' optimizes convenience, not risk, and would leave the high-risk units unexamined."},{"label":"Given the budget, which two units should be selected first?","hint":"Highest residual risk wins the slots","options":["A (payroll interface) and C (patient portal)","B (cafeteria POS) and D (print-server share)","A (payroll interface) and B (cafeteria POS)"],"answer":0,"explain":"A and C carry HIGH residual risk (payroll interface not audited in 3 years; a new, never-audited internet-facing portal). Selecting 'A and C' places effort on the greatest exposures. 'B and D' selects the two LOW-risk units, the opposite of risk-based planning. 'A and B' pairs one high-risk unit with a recently audited low-risk one, leaving the never-audited high-risk portal uncovered."},{"label":"How should the auditor treat management's request to add the cafeteria POS 'because staff complained'?","hint":"Independence and risk drive the plan, not popularity","options":["Add it immediately; management requests always override the risk assessment","Document the request, weigh it against residual risk, and adjust only if justified","Refuse to consider any management input to preserve independence"],"answer":1,"explain":"Auditors consider stakeholder input but the plan stays risk-based and evidence-driven. 'Document the request, weigh it against residual risk, and adjust only if justified' preserves both responsiveness and independence. 'Add it immediately; management requests always override' lets management set audit scope, impairing independence. 'Refuse to consider any management input' is needlessly rigid — input is welcome; it simply does not automatically override the risk ranking."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-02","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1A4","title":"Classifying controls in scope","brief":"You must correctly classify each control encountered in the payroll process so the report describes them accurately.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — CONTROL INVENTORY (PAYROLL)","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>C1</span> Segregation of duties: the clerk who enters new hires\n     cannot also approve pay rates.\n<span class='cy'>C2</span> A daily exception report lists any pay change > 20%\n     for supervisor review after the run.\n<span class='cy'>C3</span> Nightly backups let the team <span class='hl'>restore</span> the payroll\n     master file if a bad run corrupts it.","fields":[{"label":"How is control C1 (segregation of duties) best classified?","hint":"Stops the error/fraud before it happens","options":["Preventive control","Detective control","Corrective control"],"answer":0,"explain":"Segregation of duties stops an improper action from occurring in the first place, so it is a preventive control. 'Detective control' identifies problems after they occur, which C1 does not do. 'Corrective control' fixes or recovers after an event, which is also not C1's function."},{"label":"How is control C2 (daily exception report reviewed after the run) best classified?","hint":"Finds it after the fact","options":["Preventive control","Detective control","Corrective control"],"answer":1,"explain":"An exception report reviewed after processing identifies anomalies that already occurred, making C2 a detective control. 'Preventive control' would block the event beforehand, but C2 runs after the pay run. 'Corrective control' remediates or restores, which C2 does not do — it only flags items for review."},{"label":"How is control C3 (restore from nightly backup) best classified?","hint":"Recovers after damage","options":["Preventive control","Detective control","Corrective control"],"answer":2,"explain":"Restoring a corrupted file returns the system to a correct state after an event, which is a corrective control. 'Preventive control' would stop corruption from happening; C3 acts only after corruption. 'Detective control' identifies the problem; the backup restore fixes it rather than detecting it."},{"label":"Are these payroll controls general controls or application controls?","hint":"Embedded in one application's processing vs. the whole IT environment","options":["General IT controls that apply across the whole environment","Application controls specific to the payroll system's processing","Physical controls over the data center"],"answer":1,"explain":"These controls operate within the payroll application's own input, processing, and output, so they are application controls. 'General IT controls' apply across the environment (e.g., access administration, change management) rather than to one app's transactions. 'Physical controls over the data center' address facility security, which is unrelated to payroll transaction processing."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-03","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1B2","title":"Choosing the sampling methodology","brief":"You must pick the correct sampling approach for two different audit objectives on the same engagement.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — SAMPLING OBJECTIVES","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>OBJECTIVE 1:</span> Determine the RATE at which purchase orders\n  lack the required second approval (a control is present or not).\n<span class='cy'>OBJECTIVE 2:</span> Estimate the total DOLLAR value of misstatement\n  in the accounts-payable balance.\n<span class='dim'>Population: 40,000 POs; 12,000 AP line items.</span>","fields":[{"label":"Which sampling method fits Objective 1 (deviation RATE of a control)?","hint":"Testing presence/absence of a control","options":["Attribute sampling","Variable sampling","Judgmental (non-statistical) sampling only"],"answer":0,"explain":"Attribute sampling measures the rate of occurrence of a characteristic — here, missing approvals — so it fits Objective 1. 'Variable sampling' estimates numeric amounts (like dollars), not a yes/no deviation rate. 'Judgmental sampling only' abandons the statistical basis needed to project a defensible deviation rate across 40,000 POs."},{"label":"Which sampling method fits Objective 2 (estimate a dollar misstatement)?","hint":"Estimating a monetary amount","options":["Attribute sampling","Variable sampling","Stop-or-go sampling"],"answer":1,"explain":"Variable sampling estimates a numeric value such as a dollar amount, which is exactly Objective 2. 'Attribute sampling' measures a deviation rate, not a monetary total. 'Stop-or-go sampling' is a variant of attribute sampling used to limit sample size when few errors are expected — still a rate technique, not a dollar-value estimator."},{"label":"Objective 1 is a test of controls; what kind of test is Objective 2?","hint":"Control operation vs. monetary accuracy","options":["A compliance test","A substantive test","A walkthrough only"],"answer":1,"explain":"Estimating monetary misstatement examines the accuracy of balances themselves, which is a substantive test. 'A compliance test' verifies whether a control operated (Objective 1's purpose), not the dollar accuracy of a balance. 'A walkthrough only' traces one transaction to understand a process and cannot quantify misstatement across the population."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-04","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1B3","title":"Selecting the strongest audit evidence","brief":"You must decide which evidence best supports a conclusion and how to gather it reliably.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — EVIDENCE OPTIONS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>ASSERTION UNDER TEST:</span> \"Terminated employees' system\n  access is removed within 24 hours.\"\n<span class='cy'>AVAILABLE EVIDENCE:</span>\n  1. HR manager's verbal assurance it 'always happens'\n  2. Re-performed test: auditor pulls last 30 terminations\n     and checks disable timestamps against HR exit dates\n  3. A copy of the deprovisioning procedure document","fields":[{"label":"Which evidence most reliably supports the assertion?","hint":"Evidence the auditor generates is strongest","options":["The HR manager's verbal assurance","The auditor's own re-performance against system timestamps","The procedure document alone"],"answer":1,"explain":"Evidence the auditor obtains directly by re-performing the control is the most reliable, so the re-performance against system timestamps is strongest. 'The HR manager's verbal assurance' is oral and self-interested — the weakest form. 'The procedure document alone' shows intended design but not whether the control actually operated."},{"label":"Why is the verbal assurance the weakest of the three?","hint":"Source and objectivity","options":["It comes from an independent third party","It is oral, internal, and from the party being audited","It was produced by the auditor"],"answer":1,"explain":"Auditor-generated and independently sourced evidence outranks oral, internal statements from the auditee. The assurance is 'oral, internal, and from the party being audited,' so it is the least objective. 'An independent third party' would strengthen it, but HR is internal. 'Produced by the auditor' describes the re-performance, not the verbal claim."},{"label":"How should the procedure document be used in the workpaper?","hint":"Design vs. operating effectiveness","options":["As proof the control operated effectively","As evidence of control design, corroborated by testing operation","As a substitute for testing, saving time"],"answer":1,"explain":"A procedure evidences how a control is designed but not whether it ran; it should support design and be corroborated by tests of operation. 'As proof the control operated effectively' overstates a document — it cannot show real-world execution. 'As a substitute for testing' would let design stand in for operating effectiveness, leaving the assertion unverified."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-05","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1A4","title":"Compensating and overlapping controls","brief":"A key preventive control is missing; you must judge whether other controls compensate.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — CONTROL GAP ANALYSIS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>FINDING:</span> The wire-transfer system allows one operator to\n  both create AND release a wire (no segregation of duties).\n<span class='cy'>OTHER CONTROLS OBSERVED:</span>\n  - All wires > $10,000 trigger a next-day call-back to the\n    beneficiary bank by a second person.\n  - A daily wire report is reviewed and signed by the CFO.\n<span class='dim'>Average wire value last quarter: $6,400.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What type of control are the call-back and CFO review relative to the missing SoD?","hint":"They offset an absent primary control","options":["Compensating controls","Redundant preventive controls at the same point","Directive controls"],"answer":0,"explain":"Controls that reduce risk when a primary control is absent or weak are compensating controls, which is what the call-back and CFO review are here. 'Redundant preventive controls at the same point' is wrong because these are detective controls operating after the wire, not duplicate preventive checks at creation. 'Directive controls' are policies/instructions that guide behavior, not the after-the-fact checks described."},{"label":"Do the compensating controls fully cover the risk?","hint":"Look at the threshold vs. average wire value","options":["Yes — every wire is fully covered","No — wires at or below $10,000 escape the call-back","Yes — the CFO review alone eliminates all risk"],"answer":1,"explain":"The call-back only triggers above $10,000, and the average wire ($6,400) sits below it, so a residual gap remains. 'Yes — every wire is fully covered' ignores that most wires fall under the threshold. 'The CFO review alone eliminates all risk' overstates a next-day detective review, which cannot prevent an improper same-day wire from being sent."},{"label":"What should the auditor recommend?","hint":"Restore the primary control or lower the threshold","options":["Accept the gap since the CFO signs the report","Restore segregation of duties or lower the call-back threshold to cover typical wires","Remove the call-back to simplify operations"],"answer":1,"explain":"The strongest remediation restores the missing preventive control or extends coverage to typical wire values. 'Restore segregation of duties or lower the call-back threshold' closes the residual gap. 'Accept the gap since the CFO signs the report' relies on a detective control that cannot stop a fraudulent same-day wire under the threshold. 'Remove the call-back' would eliminate an existing mitigation, worsening the exposure."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-06","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1B2","title":"Selecting the right audit type","brief":"Management asks for four different reviews; you must name the correct audit type for each objective.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — ENGAGEMENT REQUESTS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>R1</span> Verify the firm follows its own change-management policy\n     and applicable SOX requirements.\n<span class='cy'>R2</span> Reconstruct events after a suspected fraudulent journal\n     entry, preserving evidence for possible litigation.\n<span class='cy'>R3</span> Evaluate whether the data-center operations run\n     efficiently and effectively.","fields":[{"label":"Which audit type fits R1 (following policy and SOX)?","hint":"Adherence to rules and regulations","options":["Compliance audit","Forensic audit","Operational audit"],"answer":0,"explain":"Verifying adherence to internal policy and external regulation is a compliance audit, matching R1. 'Forensic audit' investigates fraud and preserves legal evidence, which is R2. 'Operational audit' assesses efficiency and effectiveness of operations, which is R3 — not conformance to rules."},{"label":"Which audit type fits R2 (reconstruct a suspected fraud for litigation)?","hint":"Evidence for legal proceedings","options":["Compliance audit","Forensic audit","Financial audit"],"answer":1,"explain":"Investigating suspected fraud while preserving evidence to legal standards is a forensic audit, exactly R2. 'Compliance audit' checks rule adherence, not fraud reconstruction. 'Financial audit' opines on the fairness of financial statements and is not aimed at evidence preservation for litigation."},{"label":"Which audit type fits R3 (efficiency and effectiveness of operations)?","hint":"Value and performance, not rules","options":["Compliance audit","Operational audit","Forensic audit"],"answer":1,"explain":"Assessing whether operations are efficient and effective is the definition of an operational audit, matching R3. 'Compliance audit' focuses on conformance to requirements, not performance. 'Forensic audit' targets fraud investigation, which R3 does not involve."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-07","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2A2","title":"Identifying the governance artifact","brief":"You must classify each governance document by type so accountability and enforceability are correctly described.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — GOVERNANCE DOCUMENT SET","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>D1</span> \"The organization shall protect information commensurate\n     with its classification.\" (board-approved, mandatory, high-level)\n<span class='cy'>D2</span> \"All servers must use AES-256 for data at rest.\"\n     (mandatory technology-specific rule)\n<span class='cy'>D3</span> \"Step 1: open the console. Step 2: enable encryption...\"\n     (exact steps for one team)\n<span class='cy'>D4</span> \"Consider rotating keys annually where feasible.\"\n     (recommended, not mandatory)","fields":[{"label":"What governance artifact is D1?","hint":"High-level mandatory intent from the top","options":["Policy","Standard","Procedure"],"answer":0,"explain":"A high-level, board-approved, mandatory statement of intent is a policy, which D1 is. 'Standard' is a specific mandatory rule (like D2's AES-256), narrower than a policy. 'Procedure' gives step-by-step instructions (like D3), not high-level direction."},{"label":"What governance artifact is D2?","hint":"Mandatory, specific, uniform requirement","options":["Policy","Standard","Guideline"],"answer":1,"explain":"A mandatory, specific, uniform rule (AES-256 on all servers) is a standard, matching D2. 'Policy' is broader and high-level, not technology-specific. 'Guideline' is advisory rather than mandatory, so it cannot be D2's compulsory rule."},{"label":"What governance artifact is D4?","hint":"Recommended, discretionary","options":["Standard","Procedure","Guideline"],"answer":2,"explain":"A recommended, non-mandatory suggestion ('consider… where feasible') is a guideline, matching D4. 'Standard' would be mandatory and specific, but D4 is discretionary. 'Procedure' is a fixed sequence of steps, which D4 is not."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-08","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2A7","title":"Data owner versus data custodian","brief":"An access dispute surfaces; you must place accountability for classification and access decisions correctly.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — DATA GOVERNANCE ROLES","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>SYSTEM:</span> Clinical research database\n<span class='cy'>PARTIES:</span>\n  - Dr. Vance, Head of Research (defines what the data is,\n    who may see it, and its sensitivity)\n  - IT Storage Team (runs the servers, applies backups,\n    enforces the access list they are given)\n  - Compliance Office (independently checks adherence)\n<span class='dim'>Question at issue: who approves a new analyst's access?</span>","fields":[{"label":"Who is the data owner for this database?","hint":"Accountable for classification and access decisions","options":["The IT Storage Team","Dr. Vance, Head of Research","The Compliance Office"],"answer":1,"explain":"The data owner is the business party accountable for classifying the data and deciding who may access it — Dr. Vance. 'The IT Storage Team' is the custodian that maintains and protects data on the owner's behalf. 'The Compliance Office' provides independent oversight and does not own access decisions."},{"label":"What is the IT Storage Team's role?","hint":"Protects and maintains, does not decide access","options":["Data owner","Data custodian","Data subject"],"answer":1,"explain":"The party that safeguards, backs up, and technically enforces the owner's access decisions is the data custodian, which describes the IT Storage Team. 'Data owner' makes the classification and access decisions (Dr. Vance). 'Data subject' is the individual the personal data is about, not the team operating the servers."},{"label":"Who should approve a new analyst's access request?","hint":"Access approval follows ownership","options":["The IT Storage Team, since they configure it","The data owner, who then directs the custodian to grant it","The Compliance Office, to keep IT independent"],"answer":1,"explain":"Access is authorized by the data owner, who then directs the custodian to implement it. 'The IT Storage Team, since they configure it' confuses technical implementation with authorization — custodians grant only what the owner approves. 'The Compliance Office' oversees and reviews access but does not approve individual grants, which would compromise its independent role."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-09","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2A5","title":"Choosing the enterprise risk response","brief":"For each identified risk you must select the ERM treatment the situation calls for.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — ERM RISK REGISTER","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>RISK 1:</span> A rarely used legacy app carries high vulnerability\n  but delivers no business value and can be switched off.\n<span class='cy'>RISK 2:</span> Fire could destroy the primary data center; the firm\n  buys business-interruption + property insurance.\n<span class='cy'>RISK 3:</span> Residual phishing risk remains after training and\n  filtering; cost to reduce it further exceeds the exposure.\n<span class='dim'>Risk appetite: low for safety, moderate for cost.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What ERM response fits RISK 1 (shut off a valueless, vulnerable app)?","hint":"Eliminate the activity entirely","options":["Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"answer":0,"explain":"Eliminating the activity that creates the risk — decommissioning the app — is risk avoidance, matching RISK 1. 'Risk transfer' shifts financial impact to a third party (like insurance), which is not what turning off an app does. 'Risk acceptance' would keep running the vulnerable app, contrary to switching it off."},{"label":"What ERM response fits RISK 2 (buying insurance for fire loss)?","hint":"Shift the financial impact to a third party","options":["Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk mitigation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Purchasing insurance moves the financial consequence to another party, which is risk transfer, exactly RISK 2. 'Risk avoidance' would stop the exposed activity, but the data center keeps operating. 'Risk mitigation' reduces likelihood or impact through controls; insurance does neither — it funds recovery after the loss."},{"label":"What ERM response fits RISK 3 (residual risk, further reduction costs more than the exposure)?","hint":"Live with what remains within appetite","options":["Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk acceptance"],"answer":2,"explain":"When residual risk is within appetite and further treatment costs more than the exposure, the rational response is risk acceptance, matching RISK 3. 'Risk avoidance' would halt the activity, which is disproportionate. 'Risk mitigation' means spending more on controls — precisely what the cost-benefit analysis rules out here."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-10","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2B2","title":"IT vendor management assurance","brief":"You audit reliance on an outsourced payroll provider and must choose the right governance evidence.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — VENDOR GOVERNANCE","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>ARRANGEMENT:</span> Payroll fully outsourced to VendorCo.\n<span class='cy'>CONTRACT INCLUDES:</span> SLA (99.9% uptime), right-to-audit\n  clause, and a required annual independent assurance report.\n<span class='cy'>AUDITOR QUESTION:</span> How to gain assurance over controls that\n  now run inside VendorCo, which the client cannot see directly?","fields":[{"label":"What is the most efficient assurance over VendorCo's internal controls?","hint":"Independent report on a service organization's controls","options":["Assume the SLA guarantees the controls work","Obtain and review an independent service-organization controls report (e.g., SOC 2)","Rely solely on VendorCo management's self-assessment"],"answer":1,"explain":"An independent assurance report on the service organization's controls provides third-party evidence the client cannot gather itself. 'Assume the SLA guarantees the controls work' confuses a performance target with control assurance — uptime says nothing about control design. 'Rely solely on VendorCo management's self-assessment' lacks independence and is the weakest basis for assurance."},{"label":"What accountability does outsourcing NOT transfer?","hint":"Delegate the function, keep the responsibility","options":["Accountability for the risk stays with the client organization","All accountability transfers to VendorCo with the function","Accountability transfers only if the contract is silent"],"answer":0,"explain":"Outsourcing a function delegates the activity but not accountability — the client remains responsible for the risk. 'All accountability transfers to VendorCo' is a classic misconception; you cannot outsource responsibility. 'Accountability transfers only if the contract is silent' is incorrect regardless of contract wording; ultimate accountability stays with the organization."},{"label":"Why does the right-to-audit clause matter to the auditor?","hint":"Preserves the ability to verify","options":["It lets the client verify VendorCo's controls directly if assurance is insufficient","It is decorative and rarely enforceable","It transfers audit responsibility to VendorCo"],"answer":0,"explain":"A right-to-audit clause preserves the client's ability to inspect the vendor's controls when independent reports are insufficient. 'It is decorative and rarely enforceable' understates a contractual right that materially supports assurance. 'It transfers audit responsibility to VendorCo' is backwards — the clause reserves the client's own audit access, it does not delegate the audit."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-11","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2A2","title":"Placing IT governance accountability","brief":"A strategy dispute reaches your engagement; you must map each decision to the correct governance body.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — GOVERNANCE STRUCTURE","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>BODIES:</span>\n  - Board of Directors (sets direction, oversees risk appetite)\n  - IT Steering Committee (aligns IT investment to business,\n    prioritizes the project portfolio)\n  - IT Operations Management (runs day-to-day delivery)\n<span class='cy'>DECISION AT ISSUE:</span> Which of three competing projects gets\n  next year's limited capital budget.","fields":[{"label":"Who should decide which projects receive the limited budget?","hint":"Aligns IT investment to business priorities","options":["The Board of Directors directly","The IT Steering Committee","IT Operations Management"],"answer":1,"explain":"Prioritizing the IT investment portfolio and aligning it to business strategy is the IT steering committee's role. 'The Board of Directors directly' sets overall direction and risk appetite but delegates portfolio prioritization. 'IT Operations Management' executes delivery once projects are chosen; it does not set investment priorities across the portfolio."},{"label":"Who is ultimately accountable for IT governance and risk appetite?","hint":"Top of the accountability chain","options":["The Board of Directors","The IT Steering Committee","The external auditor"],"answer":0,"explain":"Ultimate accountability for governance and risk appetite rests with the board of directors. 'The IT Steering Committee' operates under the board's direction to align investments, not to own the risk appetite. 'The external auditor' provides independent opinion and is never accountable for the organization's governance decisions."},{"label":"If the steering committee approves projects that violate the board's risk appetite, what should the auditor report?","hint":"Governance breakdown, not a delivery defect","options":["A minor operational scheduling issue","A governance weakness: portfolio decisions exceed the board's stated risk appetite","Nothing — the committee has authority to override the board"],"answer":1,"explain":"Decisions that breach the board's risk appetite are a governance weakness the auditor must report. 'A minor operational scheduling issue' misclassifies a strategic governance failure as routine operations. 'Nothing — the committee has authority to override the board' is false; the committee operates within the board's mandate and cannot override its risk appetite."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-12","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2A7","title":"Applying a data classification scheme","brief":"You must confirm information is classified and handled at the correct level.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — CLASSIFICATION REVIEW","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>SCHEME:</span> Public < Internal < Confidential < Restricted\n<span class='cy'>ITEMS SAMPLED:</span>\n  I1. Patient medical records, labeled \"Internal\"\n  I2. The published company holiday calendar, labeled \"Restricted\"\n  I3. Draft internal org chart, unlabeled\n<span class='dim'>Handling rules escalate with each level.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What is the issue with I1 (patient records labeled 'Internal')?","hint":"Under-classification of highly sensitive data","options":["Correctly classified — Internal is adequate","Under-classified — records should be Restricted/Confidential given sensitivity","Over-classified — should be lowered to Public"],"answer":1,"explain":"Highly sensitive medical records demand the strictest handling, so labeling them 'Internal' under-classifies them. 'Correctly classified — Internal is adequate' underprotects regulated health data. 'Over-classified — should be lowered to Public' is the opposite error and would expose the most sensitive data the organization holds."},{"label":"What is the issue with I2 (public holiday calendar labeled 'Restricted')?","hint":"Over-classification wastes controls","options":["Correctly classified","Over-classified — public information does not need Restricted handling","Under-classified — should be Confidential"],"answer":1,"explain":"Already-published, non-sensitive information does not warrant the highest controls, so 'Restricted' over-classifies it and wastes protective effort. 'Correctly classified' ignores that the data is public. 'Under-classified — should be Confidential' pushes it even higher, compounding the over-classification of information anyone can already read."},{"label":"What is the primary control weakness shown by I3 (unlabeled draft)?","hint":"No label means no handling rules apply","options":["Unlabeled data has no assigned handling rules and defaults to unprotected","It is fine because drafts are temporary","Drafts are automatically Restricted by default"],"answer":0,"explain":"Without a classification label, no handling rules attach and the data risks being treated as unprotected. 'It is fine because drafts are temporary' ignores that unlabeled sensitive drafts can leak. 'Drafts are automatically Restricted by default' assumes a protective default the scheme does not state; the real weakness is that classification was never applied."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-13","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3A4","title":"Placing the control in the SDLC","brief":"You review a development project and must identify where each control belongs in the life cycle.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — SDLC CONTROL POINTS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>PROJECT:</span> New customer onboarding application\n<span class='cy'>OBSERVATIONS:</span>\n  O1. Security and data-privacy requirements were written into\n      the signed-off requirements before any code was built.\n  O2. A code review and static analysis run before merge.\n  O3. Users formally confirm the app meets their needs prior\n      to go-live acceptance.","fields":[{"label":"O1 (security requirements captured up front) belongs to which SDLC phase?","hint":"Cheapest place to build in security","options":["Requirements/definition phase","Deployment phase","Post-implementation review"],"answer":0,"explain":"Defining security and privacy needs at the outset places the control in the requirements phase, where fixing gaps is cheapest. 'Deployment phase' is far too late to originate requirements. 'Post-implementation review' evaluates results after go-live and cannot substitute for building requirements in early."},{"label":"O2 (code review and static analysis before merge) belongs to which phase?","hint":"Verifying the code as it is built","options":["Requirements phase","Development/build phase","Business case phase"],"answer":1,"explain":"Reviewing and analyzing code as it is written is a development/build-phase control, matching O2. 'Requirements phase' precedes any code, so code review cannot occur there. 'Business case phase' justifies the project financially and predates construction entirely."},{"label":"O3 (users confirm the app meets their needs) is which control?","hint":"The customer accepts the delivered system","options":["User acceptance testing (UAT)","Unit testing","Feasibility analysis"],"answer":0,"explain":"Users formally confirming the system meets their needs before go-live is user acceptance testing. 'Unit testing' checks individual code components by developers, not user-level acceptance. 'Feasibility analysis' assesses viability before the project starts and is unrelated to end-user acceptance of a built system."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-14","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3B1","title":"Choosing the implementation-testing type","brief":"For each testing objective you must name the correct test so defects surface at the right level.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — TEST STRATEGY","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>T1</span> Confirm two modules exchange data correctly across\n     their new interface.\n<span class='cy'>T2</span> After a bug fix, confirm previously working features\n     still work.\n<span class='cy'>T3</span> Verify the whole assembled system meets all specified\n     functional and non-functional requirements end to end.","fields":[{"label":"Which test fits T1 (two modules exchanging data)?","hint":"Interfaces between components","options":["Unit testing","Integration testing","Regression testing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Verifying that modules work together across their interface is integration testing, matching T1. 'Unit testing' isolates a single component and would not exercise the interface. 'Regression testing' re-checks existing features after a change, which is T2's purpose, not interface verification."},{"label":"Which test fits T2 (confirm existing features still work after a fix)?","hint":"Re-checking after a change","options":["Integration testing","Regression testing","Acceptance testing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Re-verifying that prior functionality still works after a change is regression testing, exactly T2. 'Integration testing' targets inter-module data flow (T1). 'Acceptance testing' confirms user requirements are met, not that a fix left existing features intact."},{"label":"Which test fits T3 (whole assembled system against all requirements)?","hint":"Complete integrated system, all requirements","options":["System testing","Unit testing","Smoke testing"],"answer":0,"explain":"Validating the complete integrated system against all specified requirements is system testing, matching T3. 'Unit testing' checks only individual components. 'Smoke testing' is a quick sanity check that core functions run, not a full end-to-end verification of all requirements."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-15","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3B3","title":"Selecting the changeover strategy","brief":"You must recommend the conversion approach whose risk profile matches the situation.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — CONVERSION OPTIONS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>SYSTEM:</span> Core banking ledger — zero tolerance for a\n  posting error; must be able to fall back instantly.\n<span class='cy'>STRATEGIES CONSIDERED:</span>\n  A. Direct cutover: switch off old, switch on new overnight.\n  B. Parallel run: run old and new together, compare outputs,\n     then retire the old system once confidence is high.\n  C. Phased: migrate one branch at a time.\n<span class='dim'>Budget allows brief duplicate processing.</span>","fields":[{"label":"Which changeover strategy best fits a zero-error-tolerance core ledger?","hint":"Run both and compare before committing","options":["Direct cutover","Parallel run","Big-bang with no fallback"],"answer":1,"explain":"Running old and new systems together and comparing outputs gives a fallback and continuous verification, ideal for zero-tolerance systems — the parallel run. 'Direct cutover' offers no fallback if the new system fails, the riskiest choice for critical data. 'Big-bang with no fallback' is essentially the same high-risk cutover and directly conflicts with the need to fall back instantly."},{"label":"What is the main drawback of the parallel run the auditor should note?","hint":"Cost of doing everything twice","options":["It has no way to detect errors","It is the cheapest and fastest option","It costs more because both systems run and outputs are double-processed"],"answer":2,"explain":"Parallel running duplicates processing effort and cost, which is its principal drawback. 'It has no way to detect errors' is false — comparing outputs is precisely how it detects them. 'It is the cheapest and fastest option' is wrong; running two systems is the most resource-intensive approach."},{"label":"When is a direct cutover the more appropriate choice?","hint":"Low criticality, simple, cheap-to-reverse systems","options":["For low-risk, non-critical systems where brief downtime is acceptable","For the most mission-critical systems with no tolerance for error","Never, under any circumstances"],"answer":0,"explain":"Direct cutover suits low-risk, non-critical systems where a short interruption is tolerable and duplicate processing is not justified. 'For the most mission-critical systems with no tolerance for error' is the opposite of when to use it — those need a fallback. 'Never, under any circumstances' overstates the case; cutover is valid where risk and cost tradeoffs favor it."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-16","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3B4","title":"Post-implementation review actions","brief":"Sixty days after go-live you must choose the correct post-implementation review activity.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — POST-IMPLEMENTATION REVIEW","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>SYSTEM:</span> New expense-management app, live 60 days.\n<span class='cy'>PIR OBJECTIVES:</span>\n  - Confirm the business benefits in the business case were realized.\n  - Confirm controls designed in build actually operate in production.\n  - Capture lessons learned for future projects.\n<span class='dim'>Change requests are already piling up.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What is the primary purpose of a post-implementation review?","hint":"Did it deliver what was promised?","options":["To assign blame for any project overruns","To confirm the system met its objectives and expected benefits were realized","To begin gathering requirements for the next system"],"answer":1,"explain":"A PIR confirms the delivered system met its objectives and the projected benefits were actually realized. 'To assign blame for overruns' misframes a constructive review as a fault-finding exercise. 'To begin gathering requirements for the next system' is a separate initiation activity, not the purpose of reviewing the system just deployed."},{"label":"During the PIR the auditor finds a control designed in build was never enabled in production. What is the correct action?","hint":"Design vs. operating effectiveness gap","options":["Ignore it because the design document shows the control exists","Raise a finding: the control was designed but is not operating in production","Wait for the next annual audit to mention it"],"answer":1,"explain":"A control that exists on paper but does not operate is a live gap the auditor must report now. 'Ignore it because the design document shows the control exists' confuses design with operation — a disabled control provides no assurance. 'Wait for the next annual audit' needlessly leaves a known control gap open in production."},{"label":"How should lessons learned be handled?","hint":"Feed them forward","options":["Documented and fed into future project governance to improve outcomes","Discarded once the project closes","Kept confidential from the project management office"],"answer":0,"explain":"Lessons learned are documented and fed into future project governance so mistakes are not repeated. 'Discarded once the project closes' throws away the review's forward value. 'Kept confidential from the PMO' hides exactly the insights the office needs to improve future delivery."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-17","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3B1","title":"Classifying application controls","brief":"You must classify each embedded application control so the report describes the processing risk accurately.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — APPLICATION CONTROLS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>APP:</span> Online loan-application intake\n<span class='cy'>CONTROLS OBSERVED:</span>\n  AC1. The form rejects a national ID that fails its check-digit test.\n  AC2. Batch totals of records submitted are compared to records processed.\n  AC3. The approval decision and amount are written to a read-only\n       audit log the user cannot alter.","fields":[{"label":"AC1 (check-digit validation on input) is which type of application control?","hint":"Where does the data enter?","options":["Input control","Processing control","Output control"],"answer":0,"explain":"Validating a value as it is entered is an input control, which AC1 is. 'Processing control' governs calculations and updates after data is accepted, not the initial edit check. 'Output control' governs the accuracy and distribution of results, which AC1 does not address."},{"label":"AC2 (batch totals in vs. processed) is which type of application control?","hint":"Completeness during processing","options":["Input control","Processing control","Physical control"],"answer":1,"explain":"Reconciling record counts submitted against records processed verifies completeness during processing, a processing control. 'Input control' validates data at entry, not the through-processing reconciliation. 'Physical control' concerns facility security, which is unrelated to batch reconciliation logic."},{"label":"AC3 (tamper-proof audit log of the decision) most directly supports which objective?","hint":"Can we trust the record after the fact?","options":["Data integrity and non-repudiation of the recorded decision","Faster processing throughput","Reduced storage cost"],"answer":0,"explain":"A read-only log the user cannot alter protects the integrity of the record and supports non-repudiation of the decision. 'Faster processing throughput' is a performance goal unrelated to logging. 'Reduced storage cost' is contradicted by adding an immutable log, which consumes additional storage."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-18","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3A4","title":"Evaluating the business case and feasibility","brief":"Before the build begins you must judge whether the project justification holds up.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — BUSINESS CASE REVIEW","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>PROPOSAL:</span> Replace the CRM at a cost of $2.0M.\n<span class='cy'>CLAIMED BENEFITS:</span> $0.3M/yr savings; \"strategic alignment.\"\n<span class='cy'>FEASIBILITY NOTES:</span> Vendor has no clients at our scale;\n  in-house team lacks the required skills; timeline assumes\n  no staff turnover.\n<span class='dim'>Break-even by simple math: ~6.7 years.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What is the most significant weakness in this business case?","hint":"Do the numbers justify the spend?","options":["The benefits are quantified too precisely","The costs far outweigh quantified benefits, with a very long payback","The strategic-alignment claim is too specific"],"answer":1,"explain":"A $2.0M spend recovering $0.3M/yr yields a ~6.7-year payback, so quantified costs far exceed benefits over any reasonable horizon. 'The benefits are quantified too precisely' is not a defect — precision aids evaluation. 'The strategic-alignment claim is too specific' is wrong; if anything, that claim is vague and unquantified, which is a separate concern."},{"label":"The feasibility notes reveal which type of risk?","hint":"Can the team actually deliver it?","options":["Technical and operational feasibility risk","Only financial reporting risk","No risk — feasibility is not the auditor's concern"],"answer":0,"explain":"An unproven vendor at scale, a skills gap, and a fragile timeline are technical and operational feasibility risks. 'Only financial reporting risk' ignores the delivery-capability problems the notes describe. 'No risk — feasibility is not the auditor's concern' is false; assessing whether a project can realistically be delivered is squarely within scope."},{"label":"What should the auditor recommend before approval proceeds?","hint":"Strengthen the justification first","options":["Approve as is to avoid delaying the business","Revalidate benefits, address the skills/vendor gaps, and reassess before committing funds","Cancel all CRM modernization permanently"],"answer":1,"explain":"The right course is to revalidate benefits and mitigate the feasibility gaps before funds are committed. 'Approve as is to avoid delaying the business' commits $2.0M to a weakly justified, high-risk project. 'Cancel all CRM modernization permanently' overreaches — the issue is this business case, not the entire objective of modernizing."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-19","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4A7","title":"Problem management versus incident management","brief":"A recurring outage lands on your desk; you must separate incident handling from problem management.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — SERVICE EVENT LOG","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>EVENT:</span> The order-entry service has crashed 5 times this\n  month. Each time the on-call team restarts it and service\n  resumes in minutes.\n<span class='cy'>OBSERVED:</span> No one has determined WHY it keeps crashing.\n<span class='dim'>ITIL definitions apply: incident = unplanned interruption;\n  problem = underlying cause of one or more incidents.</span>","fields":[{"label":"Each individual crash-and-restart is handled by which process?","hint":"Restore service fast","options":["Incident management","Problem management","Capacity management"],"answer":0,"explain":"Restoring normal service as quickly as possible after an unplanned interruption is incident management, which each crash-and-restart represents. 'Problem management' seeks the underlying cause, which the restarts do not do. 'Capacity management' plans for adequate resources over time and is not what a crash restart addresses."},{"label":"Finding out WHY the service keeps crashing is the job of which process?","hint":"Underlying root cause of repeated incidents","options":["Incident management","Problem management","Change management"],"answer":1,"explain":"Determining the root cause of one or more incidents is problem management, matching the unanswered 'why.' 'Incident management' only restores service and does not investigate root cause. 'Change management' controls how changes are approved and deployed, not root-cause analysis of recurring failures."},{"label":"What audit finding best captures the gap here?","hint":"Symptoms treated, cause ignored","options":["Incidents are being resolved but no problem management is investigating the recurring root cause","The team responds too slowly to incidents","There is nothing to report; service always resumes"],"answer":0,"explain":"The organization treats symptoms repeatedly without invoking problem management to eliminate the root cause — that is the gap. 'The team responds too slowly' is contradicted by the log, which shows fast restarts. 'There is nothing to report' ignores five recurring outages whose cause remains unknown, a clear resilience weakness."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-20","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4A8","title":"Change and patch control decisions","brief":"An emergency patch is proposed for production; you must confirm the right change controls apply.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — EMERGENCY CHANGE REQUEST","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>REQUEST:</span> Apply a critical security patch to the production\n  payment gateway TONIGHT to close an actively exploited flaw.\n<span class='cy'>PROPOSED:</span> \"Skip CAB approval and testing to move fast;\n  document it later.\"\n<span class='dim'>An emergency-change procedure exists but is being bypassed.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What is the correct handling of an emergency change?","hint":"Emergency ≠ uncontrolled","options":["Apply it with no approval or record since it is urgent","Follow the emergency-change procedure: expedited approval, then retroactive documentation and review","Wait for the next monthly change window regardless of the exploit"],"answer":1,"explain":"Emergencies use an expedited but still controlled path — emergency approval, then prompt retroactive documentation and review. 'Apply it with no approval or record' abandons control entirely and defeats auditability. 'Wait for the next monthly change window' ignores an actively exploited flaw, exposing the payment gateway needlessly."},{"label":"Why is skipping ALL testing on the payment gateway risky?","hint":"Untested change to a critical system","options":["An untested patch could break payment processing or introduce new faults","Testing is never required for security patches","The gateway is not important enough to test"],"answer":0,"explain":"An untested change to a critical payment system may break processing or add new defects, so at least minimal validation is warranted even in an emergency. 'Testing is never required for security patches' is false — patches can regress functionality. 'The gateway is not important enough to test' contradicts its status as a critical production payment system."},{"label":"What must exist after the emergency patch is applied?","hint":"Preserve the audit trail","options":["A back-dated record created only if an auditor asks","A documented, approved change record and post-implementation review of the emergency change","Nothing, since emergency changes are exempt from records"],"answer":1,"explain":"Every emergency change needs a documented, approved record and a post-implementation review to preserve the audit trail. 'A back-dated record created only if an auditor asks' is not a genuine control and undermines integrity. 'Nothing, since emergency changes are exempt' is false — the expedited path defers, but never eliminates, documentation and review."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-21","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4B1","title":"Reading the resilience metrics","brief":"During BIA review you must match each stated recovery requirement to the correct resilience metric.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — BIA RECOVERY REQUIREMENTS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>SYSTEM:</span> Online trading platform\n<span class='cy'>REQUIREMENTS:</span>\n  R1. \"After a disruption, the platform must be back online\n      within 2 hours.\"\n  R2. \"We can afford to lose at most 5 minutes of transaction\n      data.\"\n  R3. \"The business cannot survive if the platform is down for\n      more than 8 hours total.\"","fields":[{"label":"R1 ('back online within 2 hours') defines which metric?","hint":"Time to restore service","options":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)"],"answer":0,"explain":"The target time to restore a service after disruption is the Recovery Time Objective, which R1 states. 'Recovery Point Objective' measures tolerable data loss, not restoration time. 'Maximum Tolerable Downtime' is the absolute outer limit before the business fails, which is R3, not the 2-hour restore target."},{"label":"R2 ('lose at most 5 minutes of data') defines which metric?","hint":"How much data loss is acceptable","options":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Mean Time To Repair (MTTR)"],"answer":1,"explain":"The maximum acceptable data loss measured back in time is the Recovery Point Objective, exactly R2's 5 minutes. 'Recovery Time Objective' is about restoration time, not data loss. 'Mean Time To Repair' is an average repair duration statistic, not a tolerable-data-loss target."},{"label":"R3 ('cannot survive down more than 8 hours') defines which metric?","hint":"The absolute survival ceiling","options":["Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Time Objective (RTO)"],"answer":1,"explain":"The absolute maximum outage the business can survive is the Maximum Tolerable Downtime, which R3 states as 8 hours. 'Recovery Point Objective' addresses data loss, not outage duration. 'Recovery Time Objective' is the planned restore target (2 hours here) and must be shorter than the MTD ceiling, so it is not R3."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-22","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4B5","title":"Selecting the DR site strategy","brief":"You must recommend a recovery-site option whose cost and recovery speed fit the requirement.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — DR SITE OPTIONS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>REQUIREMENT:</span> RTO of 1 hour for a critical claims system;\n  budget is available.\n<span class='cy'>OPTIONS:</span>\n  A. Cold site: space and power only; hardware/data loaded\n     after a disaster (days to recover).\n  B. Warm site: some hardware pre-installed; data restored\n     from backups (hours to recover).\n  C. Hot site: fully configured, near-real-time replicated\n     data; ready almost immediately.","fields":[{"label":"Which site best meets a 1-hour RTO for a critical system?","hint":"Fastest recovery, highest cost","options":["Cold site","Warm site","Hot site"],"answer":2,"explain":"A hot site is fully configured with replicated data and can take over almost immediately, meeting a tight 1-hour RTO. 'Cold site' takes days to stand up and cannot meet an hour. 'Warm site' recovers in hours, likely exceeding the 1-hour target for a critical system."},{"label":"What is the main trade-off of the hot site?","hint":"Speed costs money","options":["It is the cheapest option but slowest","It is the most expensive to maintain but recovers fastest","It cannot replicate data"],"answer":1,"explain":"A hot site delivers the fastest recovery at the highest ongoing cost — that is the core trade-off. 'It is the cheapest but slowest' describes a cold site, the opposite. 'It cannot replicate data' is false; near-real-time replication is exactly what makes a hot site fast."},{"label":"If the RTO were relaxed to 3 days with a tight budget, which site becomes appropriate?","hint":"Match cost to a loose recovery window","options":["Hot site","Cold site","Neither — a hot site is always required"],"answer":1,"explain":"With a 3-day window and a tight budget, a cold site's low cost and multi-day recovery become acceptable. 'Hot site' would over-provision and overspend for a loose RTO. 'Neither — a hot site is always required' is wrong; site choice should match the recovery requirement and budget, not default to the most expensive option."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-23","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4B1","title":"Choosing the backup scheme","brief":"You must evaluate a backup design against restore-time and storage constraints.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — BACKUP STRATEGY","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>DEFINITIONS:</span>\n  Full: copies all data every time.\n  Incremental: copies only data changed since the LAST backup\n    (full or incremental).\n  Differential: copies all data changed since the last FULL backup.\n<span class='cy'>CONSTRAINT:</span> Nightly window is short; restores must be fast\n  and simple. A weekly full runs Sunday.","fields":[{"label":"Which scheme uses the LEAST nightly backup time/space between fulls?","hint":"Only what changed since the last backup of any kind","options":["Incremental","Differential","Full every night"],"answer":0,"explain":"Incremental backups copy only what changed since the last backup of any type, minimizing nightly time and space. 'Differential' copies everything since the last full, growing larger each night. 'Full every night' copies all data nightly, the most time- and space-intensive option."},{"label":"Which scheme makes RESTORES simplest (fewest sets to apply)?","hint":"Trade nightly cost for restore simplicity","options":["Incremental","Differential","Full plus every incremental in order"],"answer":1,"explain":"Differential restores need only the last full plus one differential, making restores simpler than incremental chains. 'Incremental' restores require the full plus every incremental applied in sequence — more sets, more fragile. 'Full plus every incremental in order' is precisely the more complex restore path differential avoids."},{"label":"Given a short nightly window AND a need for fast, simple restores, what is the key trade-off to flag?","hint":"Nightly speed vs. restore speed","options":["Incremental is fastest nightly but slowest/riskiest to restore; differential restores faster at higher nightly cost","There is no trade-off; incremental wins on every dimension","Full nightly is the only acceptable choice"],"answer":0,"explain":"The auditor should flag the classic trade-off: incremental minimizes nightly cost but complicates restores, while differential restores faster at a higher nightly cost. 'There is no trade-off; incremental wins on every dimension' ignores incremental's slower, chain-dependent restore. 'Full nightly is the only acceptable choice' overreacts, given the short nightly window that fulls would strain."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-24","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4A8","title":"Configuration and patch baseline","brief":"You review whether servers match an approved baseline and how deviations are handled.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — CONFIGURATION REVIEW","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>BASELINE:</span> Approved gold image defines required patch level,\n  disabled services, and hardening settings.\n<span class='cy'>SCAN RESULTS:</span>\n  S1. 3 servers are 2 patch levels behind the baseline.\n  S2. 1 server has Telnet enabled (baseline requires it disabled).\n  S3. No record shows who approved these deviations.","fields":[{"label":"What does S1 (servers behind the patch baseline) indicate?","hint":"Drift from the approved state","options":["Configuration drift / patch-management weakness","A stronger-than-required security posture","An acceptable, expected state"],"answer":0,"explain":"Servers lagging the approved patch level show configuration drift and a patch-management weakness. 'A stronger-than-required security posture' is the opposite — being behind is weaker, not stronger. 'An acceptable, expected state' contradicts the baseline, which defines the required patch level the servers fail to meet."},{"label":"S2 (Telnet enabled against baseline) is best described as what?","hint":"Insecure service violating hardening","options":["A hardening violation exposing cleartext credentials","A performance optimization","A required baseline setting"],"answer":0,"explain":"Telnet transmits credentials in cleartext and violates the hardening baseline, so it is a hardening violation. 'A performance optimization' is irrelevant and false. 'A required baseline setting' is contradicted by the baseline, which explicitly requires Telnet disabled."},{"label":"What governance gap does S3 (no approval record for deviations) reveal?","hint":"Undocumented exceptions","options":["Deviations lack an approved exception/change record, breaking accountability","Nothing — undocumented deviations are normal","The baseline itself is invalid"],"answer":0,"explain":"Deviations without an approved exception or change record break accountability and traceability — a governance gap. 'Nothing — undocumented deviations are normal' normalizes exactly the control failure at issue. 'The baseline itself is invalid' misplaces the fault; the baseline is sound, the undocumented deviations from it are the problem."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-25","format":5,"domain":5,"obj":"5A3","title":"Choosing the access-control model","brief":"You must match each access requirement to the correct access-control model or principle.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — ACCESS CONTROL DESIGN","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>REQUIREMENTS:</span>\n  Q1. Access is granted based on the user's job role\n      (Teller, Manager, Auditor), not per individual.\n  Q2. In a classified system, the SYSTEM enforces labels\n      (Secret, Top Secret); users cannot change them.\n  Q3. A user should hold only the minimum rights needed\n      to do their job — no more.","fields":[{"label":"Q1 (access by job role) describes which model?","hint":"Roles carry the permissions","options":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)"],"answer":0,"explain":"Granting access based on job role rather than individual identity is Role-Based Access Control. 'Discretionary Access Control' lets data owners grant access at their discretion, not by predefined role. 'Mandatory Access Control' uses system-enforced labels, which is Q2's scenario, not role assignment."},{"label":"Q2 (system-enforced labels users cannot change) describes which model?","hint":"The system, not the user, decides","options":["Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)"],"answer":1,"explain":"System-enforced sensitivity labels that users cannot override is Mandatory Access Control, matching Q2. 'Discretionary Access Control' would let users grant access themselves, which MAC forbids. 'Role-Based Access Control' assigns rights by role but does not impose non-overridable classification labels the way MAC does."},{"label":"Q3 (minimum rights needed) states which principle?","hint":"Grant no more than necessary","options":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Defense in depth"],"answer":0,"explain":"Granting only the minimum rights required is the principle of least privilege, exactly Q3. 'Separation of duties' splits a sensitive task among people to prevent fraud — a different control. 'Defense in depth' layers multiple controls and is not about limiting an individual's rights to the minimum."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-26","format":5,"domain":5,"obj":"5A6","title":"Selecting the cryptographic mechanism","brief":"For each protection goal you must choose the correct cryptographic mechanism.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — CRYPTO REQUIREMENTS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>GOALS:</span>\n  G1. Encrypt a 10 GB nightly database export efficiently\n      between two internal systems that share a secret key.\n  G2. Prove a message came from the sender and was not altered,\n      so the sender cannot deny sending it.\n  G3. Verify a downloaded file's integrity without any secret key.","fields":[{"label":"Which mechanism best fits G1 (fast bulk encryption with a shared key)?","hint":"Same key both ends, fast for bulk data","options":["Symmetric encryption (e.g., AES)","Asymmetric encryption (e.g., RSA) for the whole 10 GB","A hash function"],"answer":0,"explain":"Symmetric encryption uses one shared key and is fast for bulk data, ideal for a 10 GB export. 'Asymmetric encryption for the whole 10 GB' is far too slow for bulk data; it is used to exchange keys, not encrypt large payloads. 'A hash function' provides integrity, not confidentiality, so it cannot encrypt the export."},{"label":"Which mechanism fits G2 (authenticity, integrity, and non-repudiation)?","hint":"Sign with the private key","options":["A digital signature (hash encrypted with the sender's private key)","Symmetric encryption with a shared key","A simple checksum"],"answer":0,"explain":"A digital signature — a hash signed with the sender's private key — proves origin and integrity and provides non-repudiation, matching G2. 'Symmetric encryption with a shared key' cannot prove which party sent it, since both share the key, defeating non-repudiation. 'A simple checksum' detects accidental changes but offers no authenticity or non-repudiation."},{"label":"Which mechanism fits G3 (verify file integrity with no secret key)?","hint":"One-way digest, publicly comparable","options":["A cryptographic hash (e.g., SHA-256)","Symmetric encryption","A private key"],"answer":0,"explain":"A cryptographic hash produces a digest anyone can recompute and compare without a secret, verifying integrity — exactly G3. 'Symmetric encryption' requires a shared secret key and provides confidentiality, not keyless integrity checking. 'A private key' is used for signing/decryption, not for a keyless integrity check of a public download."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-27","format":5,"domain":5,"obj":"5A7","title":"PKI trust and certificate validation","brief":"You review how the organization establishes and validates certificate trust.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — PKI REVIEW","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>ENVIRONMENT:</span> Internal PKI with a Certificate Authority (CA).\n<span class='cy'>OBSERVATIONS:</span>\n  P1. Servers present certificates signed by the internal CA;\n      clients trust the CA's root certificate.\n  P2. A revoked certificate was still accepted last week.\n  P3. The CA's private key is stored on a shared network drive.","fields":[{"label":"In P1, what makes clients trust a server's certificate?","hint":"Chain of trust to a trusted root","options":["The certificate chains to a CA root the client already trusts","The server IP address is on an allow list","The certificate is newer than the client"],"answer":0,"explain":"Trust flows because the certificate chains to a CA root the client already trusts. 'The server IP address is on an allow list' is a network control, not how certificate trust is established. 'The certificate is newer than the client' is irrelevant to PKI validation, which depends on the signing chain, not relative age."},{"label":"P2 (a revoked certificate was accepted) points to which control failure?","hint":"Checking revocation status","options":["Revocation checking (CRL/OCSP) is not being enforced","The certificate expired too early","The key length is too short"],"answer":0,"explain":"Accepting a revoked certificate means revocation checking via CRL or OCSP is not enforced. 'The certificate expired too early' is a different lifecycle issue and would cause rejection, not acceptance. 'The key length is too short' concerns cryptographic strength, unrelated to whether revocation status was checked."},{"label":"P3 (CA private key on a shared drive) is what severity of issue?","hint":"Compromise here breaks the whole PKI","options":["Critical — a compromised CA private key lets an attacker forge any certificate","Low — private keys are meant to be shared","Moderate — only affects one server"],"answer":0,"explain":"The CA private key is the root of trust; if stolen, an attacker can forge trusted certificates for anything, so exposure is critical. 'Low — private keys are meant to be shared' is dangerously wrong; the CA key must be tightly protected, ideally in an HSM. 'Moderate — only affects one server' understates it — CA compromise undermines the entire PKI, not one server."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-28","format":5,"domain":5,"obj":"5A3","title":"Access review and segregation of duties","brief":"A user-access review surfaces conflicts; you must apply the correct IAM decisions.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — USER ACCESS REVIEW","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>FINDINGS:</span>\n  F1. One user can both create a vendor AND approve payments\n      to that vendor.\n  F2. A contractor who left 4 months ago still has an active\n      account.\n  F3. \"Admin\" rights were granted to 30 users \"to save time\";\n      only 3 need them.","fields":[{"label":"F1 (create vendor AND approve its payments) violates which principle?","hint":"One person controls a whole risky transaction","options":["Separation (segregation) of duties","Defense in depth","Data classification"],"answer":0,"explain":"One person controlling both vendor creation and payment approval violates separation of duties, enabling fraud. 'Defense in depth' is about layered controls, not splitting a transaction among people. 'Data classification' governs sensitivity labeling and is unrelated to conflicting transaction rights."},{"label":"F2 (departed contractor still active) is what kind of failure?","hint":"Timely removal of access","options":["A deprovisioning / timely access-revocation failure","An encryption failure","A network segmentation failure"],"answer":0,"explain":"An account left active four months after departure is a deprovisioning and timely-revocation failure. 'An encryption failure' concerns data confidentiality, not stale accounts. 'A network segmentation failure' concerns network zoning, which is unrelated to failing to disable a leaver's account."},{"label":"F3 (30 admins where 3 suffice) violates which principle, and what is the fix?","hint":"Grant only what is needed","options":["Least privilege — reduce admin rights to only the users who require them","Non-repudiation — add more logging","Availability — grant everyone admin to avoid delays"],"answer":0,"explain":"Excess admin grants violate least privilege; the fix is to restrict admin rights to the few who genuinely need them. 'Non-repudiation — add more logging' does not address the over-provisioning itself. 'Availability — grant everyone admin to avoid delays' worsens the problem by expanding, not reducing, privileged access."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-29","format":5,"domain":5,"obj":"5A3","title":"Applying network and endpoint controls","brief":"You must match each protection requirement to the correct network or endpoint control.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — NETWORK CONTROL DESIGN","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>REQUIREMENTS:</span>\n  N1. Isolate the payment-card systems from the general\n      corporate LAN so a breach cannot spread.\n  N2. Detect AND automatically block known malicious traffic\n      inline at the perimeter.\n  N3. Prevent sensitive files from being emailed outside\n      the organization.","fields":[{"label":"Which control fits N1 (isolate cardholder systems)?","hint":"Contain the blast radius","options":["Network segmentation","A single flat network","Disabling all logging"],"answer":0,"explain":"Placing cardholder systems in their own segment limits how far a breach can spread — network segmentation. 'A single flat network' is the opposite, letting an intrusion move freely. 'Disabling all logging' removes visibility and does nothing to isolate systems."},{"label":"Which control fits N2 (detect AND block malicious traffic inline)?","hint":"Active inline prevention, not just alerting","options":["An intrusion detection system (IDS) only","An intrusion prevention system (IPS)","A honeypot"],"answer":1,"explain":"An IPS sits inline and can both detect and automatically block malicious traffic, matching N2. 'An IDS only' detects and alerts but does not block, so it cannot satisfy the block requirement. 'A honeypot' lures and studies attackers; it does not block traffic to production systems."},{"label":"Which control fits N3 (stop sensitive files leaving via email)?","hint":"Inspect and stop data exfiltration","options":["Data Loss Prevention (DLP)","A stronger Wi-Fi password","Full-disk encryption"],"answer":0,"explain":"DLP inspects outbound content and blocks sensitive data from leaving, exactly N3. 'A stronger Wi-Fi password' controls network access, not data exfiltration over email. 'Full-disk encryption' protects data at rest on a lost device but does nothing to stop a user emailing a file out."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-30","format":5,"domain":5,"obj":"5B5","title":"Ordering the incident-response steps","brief":"An active malware outbreak is underway; you must choose the correct incident-response action at each stage.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — INCIDENT RESPONSE","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>SITUATION:</span> Ransomware is spreading across file servers RIGHT\n  NOW. The IR plan follows: detection → containment →\n  eradication → recovery → lessons learned, with evidence\n  preserved throughout.\n<span class='dim'>Question: what to do at each stage, in order.</span>","fields":[{"label":"Immediately after confirming the outbreak, what is the FIRST priority action?","hint":"Stop the spread","options":["Rebuild all servers from scratch immediately","Contain it — isolate affected systems to stop the spread","Write the lessons-learned report"],"answer":1,"explain":"After detection, the first priority is containment — isolating affected systems to halt the spread. 'Rebuild all servers from scratch immediately' is eradication/recovery and, done first, destroys evidence and skips containment. 'Write the lessons-learned report' comes at the very end, not during an active outbreak."},{"label":"After containment, what does eradication involve?","hint":"Remove the cause","options":["Removing the malware and closing the vulnerability that let it in","Paying the ransom to make it stop","Restoring service before removing the malware"],"answer":0,"explain":"Eradication removes the malware and closes the exploited vulnerability so it cannot recur. 'Paying the ransom' is not eradication and provides no assurance the threat is removed. 'Restoring service before removing the malware' would reinfect the environment — recovery must follow eradication, not precede it."},{"label":"Throughout the response, what must the team preserve for possible legal action?","hint":"Maintain evidentiary integrity","options":["Evidence with a documented chain of custody","Only a screenshot taken at the end","Nothing — speed matters more than evidence"],"answer":0,"explain":"Evidence must be preserved with a documented chain of custody to remain admissible for legal action. 'Only a screenshot taken at the end' fails to capture volatile evidence and breaks the chain of custody. 'Nothing — speed matters more than evidence' would forfeit any ability to pursue attribution or prosecution."}]}
]);
